<http://www.e-lico.eu/data/kupo/KUPO_0200027> comment "Obese Zucker Diabetic Fatty (ZDF) rats are homozygotes for a mutation in the leptin receptor gene (Lpr), thus reducing the affinity of the leptin receptor for its ligand. Male obese ZDF rats are glucose-intolerant, transiently hyperinsulinemic, hyperlipidemic, hyperleptinemic and develop mild nephropathy. Female obese ZDF rats do not express the diabetic phenotype only on diabetogenic diet, not on regular chow diet. Lean ZDF rats, whether male or female do not express the diabetic phenotype."^^string

<http://www.e-lico.eu/data/kupo/KUPO_0200023> comment "The susceptibility to type 1 diabetes in NOD mice is polygenic and strongly depends on environment. Diabetes develop as a result of leukocytic infiltrate of pancreatic islet (auto-immune disease). However, the onset of diabetes is very variable, as the incidence of spontaneous diabetes in the NOD mouse is 60-80% in females, but dramatically lower in males (20-30%). Female NOD mice exhibit increased glomerular area, glomerulosclerosis and glomerular basal membrane thickness at 50 weeks of age."^^string
<http://www.e-lico.eu/data/kupo/KUPO_0200083> comment "Intravenous injection of HSV provokes acute focal mesangial proliferative glomerulonephritis in rodents."^^string

<http://www.e-lico.eu/data/kupo/KUPO_0200011> comment "Streptozotocin (STZ) is an analogue of N-acetylglucosamine (GlcNAc). It is readily transported into pancreatic beta-cells by GLUT-2 and selectively inhibits the activity of beta-cell O-GlcNAcase, which is responsible for removing O-GlcNAc from protein. This causes irreversible O-glycosylation of intracellular proteins and results in beta-cell apoptosis. STZ can be used to study diabetic nephropathy in most rodent strains. However the severity of injury is dependent on genetic background. Moreover, GLUT-2 is also expressed by renal and hepatic cells. The cytotoxicity of STZ is thus not restricted to pancreatic beta-cells but also affects kidney and liver cells."^^string
<http://www.e-lico.eu/data/kupo/KUPO_0200017> label "High dose streptozotocin-induced model of diabetic nephropathy associated with eNOS deletion"@en

<http://www.e-lico.eu/data/kupo/KUPO_0200017> comment "This model has been developed in the nephropathy resistant C57Bl/6 background. <http://www.e-lico.eu/data/kupo/KUPO_0200011> comment "Streptozotocin (STZ) is an analogue of N-acetylglucosamine (GlcNAc). It is readily transported into pancreatic beta-cells by GLUT-2 and selectively inhibits the activity of beta-cell O-GlcNAcase, which is responsible for removing O-GlcNAc from protein. This causes irreversible O-glycosylation of intracellular proteins and results in beta-cell apoptosis. STZ can be used to study diabetic nephropathy in most rodent strains. However the severity of injury is dependent on genetic background. Moreover, GLUT-2 is also expressed by renal and hepatic cells. The cytotoxicity of STZ is thus not restricted to pancreatic beta-cells but also affects kidney and liver cells."^^string

For this reason, transgenic mice that ectopically express a mice-human chimeric Thy-1.1 antigen on podocytes have been developed. These mice slowly and spontaneously develop albuminuria and focal segmental glomerulosclerosis (FSGS). Injection of mAb directed against the Thy-1.1 antigen or against aminopeptidase (APA, an enzyme expressed in proximal tubule epithelial cells and podocytes), induces an acute albuminuria within 1 day and accelerate the development of FSGS lesions within 3 wk. FSGS lesions in this mouse model mimicks the collapsing variant of human FSGS."^^string
